    <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-8 community-content-block education" style="display: none;">
      <div class="inner-content">
        <h1>Education</h1>
        <h4 class="subtitle red with-top-margin">BRIDGE SCHOOLS</h4>

        <p>For kids who have never been to school, there's a school directly in the slum that's called a bridge school. Suppose a child is nine years old (4th grade age) but can't read or write at a 4th grade level. Before the child can attend formal school, they need to have a minimum standard of proficiency to enter that school. Bridge schools are an intense environment that gets children caught up so they can enroll in formal school. Bridge school students attend school from 8am-1pm every day.</p>

        <h4 class="subtitle red with-top-margin">FORMAL SCHOOL</h4>

        <p>Around the Khalpar area, there are a number of decent formal schools. Some of them are Bengali-medium schools (meaning the Kolkata native language of Bengali is the teaching language) and there are also English-medium schools. We send students to both. In total, there are three formal schools where the students go. The students attend their formal school from 8am-1pm every day and again from 2pm-4pm for tutoring at the project school.</p>

        <p>Altogether, the education programs in Khalpar serve 122 kids. ></p>
      </div>
    </div><!--end Education-->

    <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-8 community-content-block job-training" style="display: none;">
      <div class="inner-content">
        <h1>Job Training</h1>
        <p>Job training started in Khalpar in 2012 with a tailoring program for 16 Khalpar women, as the early efforts to coordinate increasingly meaningful and well-paying work. We now have programs in tailoring, taxi driving, cosmetology, and basic literacy.</p>

        <h4 class="subtitle red with-top-margin">TAILORING</h4>

        <p>Beginning in August 2012, 16 of the Khalpar women began a six-month tailoring class that teaches them how to sew and make clothes. Upon graduation, they received a sewing machine and a small loan to begin their business. They are now accepting orders and making clothes for the community. Our second class has just finished and is beginning to make and sell their products too.</p>

        <h4 class="subtitle red with-top-margin">TAXI DRIVING</h4>

        <p>Four boys, who range in age from 18-26, were sent to taxi driving school. One of them, Robi, now has an excellent job driving an ambulance. Two of the others gained jobs as an auto rickshaw driver and the last one is still looking for a job.</p>

        <h4 class="subtitle red with-top-margin">COSMETOLOGY</h4>

        <p>We've started a beautician training program this year. Many of the women in Khalpar work as maidservants in wealthy people's homes nearby. They have to work very long hours in return for very little pay. Beauty school has allowed students to learn a skill they enjoy and pays twice as much as being a maidservant.</p>
      </div>
    </div><!--end Job Training-->

